                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>No official record has been found of the discussion at this dinner. The
                    information given above is derived from <persName corresp="#p_ACHESONDG1"
                        >Acheson</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Present at the Creation</hi>, page
                    610. According to <persName corresp="#p_ACHESONDG1">Acheson</persName>’s brief
                    account, the discussion focused on the issue of the location of the North
                    Atlantic Council and the selection of a Secretary General for the organization.
                    According to the account in <persName corresp="#p_EDENSA1">Eden</persName>, <hi
                        rend="italic">Full Circle</hi>, page 45, <persName corresp="#p_ACHESONDG1"
                        >Acheson</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_EDENSA1">Eden</persName>
                    agreed during the meeting to the suitability of a joint American-British
                    declaration guaranteeing support for the European Defense Community in the event
                    of threats from within or without. <persName corresp="#p_ACHESONDG1"
                        >Acheson</persName> also told <persName corresp="#p_EDENSA1">Eden</persName>
                    that the United States was considering a new “Monroe Doctrine” for Europe.</p>
                <p>According to telegram 3504, February 12, from London, British Chancellor of
                    Exchequer <persName corresp="#p_BUTLERRA1">Butler</persName> and Foreign Office
                    Permanent Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_STRANGSW1">Strang</persName>
                    were also scheduled to attend the dinner. (100.11 AC/2–1252)</p>
            </div>
